I ordered on Monday night (11/16) from the 2701 14th St NW, Washington, DC 20009 location and I failed to update my phone number with the order. I somewhat-angrily called the store after waiting for 45 minutes to ask where my order was. The manager was uber-polite in explaining that they had attempted to reach me three times, and that instead of delivering less than fresh food to me they would remake my order quickly and send it out with the next available driver at no charge. The pizza arrived shortly thereafter - the delivery driver was super nice and didn't expect to even receive a tip (tipping was the absolute least I could do) and the pizza was fresh, hot and tasty (despite being ordered at 11pm on a Monday). Great experience and highly recommended - keep it up!

On one level, Domino's is a difficult place to appreciate: the pizza tastes like cardboard, it's a chain and they stopped using the Noid as their mascot. However, things are never so simple, are they?  To fully appreciate such a place, we must observe it from a more spiritual plane. Dominoes is a game of chance, representing both the randomness of the universe and our agency within it. We may not always want the pizza here, but sometimes, it's what the office ordered because it's cheap.  A reminder of our ultimate faith is worth way more than the temporal pleasures of 'good pizza,' am I wrong?  No.

They even have small slots that you would see in some banks, so that you can communicate with the person taking your order. I think maybe years and years ago I saw a Chinese carry out place that had a similar set-up. Who knows, I guess they have their reasons.  Before I came in, I already had an idea about the kind of pizza that I wanted. I located the specialty pizza on their take-out menu.  I went ahead and ordered the Pacific Veggie pizza that included a myriad array of various types of veggies!  Peppers, onions, mushrooms and even my favorite black olives. When I got home, I was able to kill off about 3 and 1/2 slices, before saving the rest in the fridge for lunch tomorrow

BAD BAD BAD for the Columbia Heights McDomino's. According to the pizza tracker, my order sat in the store for 20 minutes after employee Mariano "quality checked" it. After that, employee Fazalur took another roughly 45 minutes to deliver it. I don't know exactly how long because about 15 minutes after Fazalur allegedly left the store with my order, the pizza tracker said that my food had been delivered although it hadn't and it stopped "tracking" (if that's even what it really does). I called the store and told them the tracker said my food was delivered although it had not been, and the employee who answered indicated that it would be delivered in about another 5 minutes. About 30 minutes after this, Fazalur finally showed up. I asked if him if he had trouble finding the place, and he replied, "uhhhh...." That's literally what he said, verbatim.  Upon opening my order, I discovered that the pizza was cold (big surprise), the crust was burnt, the store gave me the wrong salad dressing, and the salad was low quality (the "spring mix" is all just iceberg lettuce, really?! Please get with the times and try romaine! It can't be THAT expensive, even for McDomino's!). I don't know what kind of "quality check" Mariano supposedly did, but in my opinion it was sub par. Pizza toppings were OK though cold, and surprisingly accurate.  I have been ordering from Domino's off and on literally throughout my life, and the reason it's been off and on is that I've been burned (no pun intended) so often. I have given many different Domino's stores many second chances, including the one on 14th Street NW in Washington, DC that I ordered from tonight and they all disappoint in relatively short order. Maybe it's time to stick with Papa John's, Pizza Hut, etc. from now on.  I suggest the company get its head (and any other body parts) out of the tomato sauce and stop giving customers a McPizza experience.  Maybe the pizza tracker should go the way of the old 30 minute guaranteed delivery time and McDomino's should get rid of it? They both create unrealistic expectations, apparently. Can employees manipulate the pizza tracker to make it look like orders have been delivered when they haven't? Hmmm....I understand being busy on a Saturday night, I used to work in food service, but let's not create unrealistic expectations.  Thank you for reading my rant and I hope this Domino's location can improve.
